latestPosts.caption:
It was at Mehendi when Conner realized, ‘Looks like at our events, we don’t just walk in—we dance our way in?’

I shrugged and ran toward the Dhol. He played along, and before I knew it, he was sitting on top of it!

Thinking back, I never really walked him through the nuances of an Indian wedding, but true to himself, he caught on effortlessly—and had the best time celebrating!

latestPosts.caption:
11.20.2024 | Marrying the love of my life, again. This time picking it up from 3 years ago when we were planning our wedding in full steam - But life had other plans, and our dream wedding took a big detour. We had a quick court wedding in June 2022 before my treatment began, with no end in sight or plans for the envisioned wedding.

When I reached remission, we dared to dream again. This time the celebration was beyond the ceremonies and tradition, but a testament to our resilience and unwavering devotion to each other. We chose to celebrate in an intimate way, with our community who stood by us through our toughest few years. Incredibly blessed to be surrounded by so much love.

We are now intentionally focused on being present & grateful, finding lightness & joy, prioritizing wellness & community.

latestPosts.caption:
Meet us on June 6, 2022. The day my heart expanded beyond anything I’ve known possible as we exchanged vows to become one. The day my home started to belong with Conner, no matter where we were. It was also the day my family doubled, as Conner’s family poured their unwavering love and support into our union.. They welcomed me with open arms, making me feel like I had always belonged. Our families blended together creating a beautiful bond between two families from opposite sides of the world.

This was also the day clouded by a terrible reality. 2 weeks ago these smiling faces had heard the terrible news of my cancer diagnosis, and in 1 week I was to start Chemo. This version of the wedding was obviously not the plan - We had our Indian wedding already on the calendar a few months away, with planning in full swing. But life had other plans, and just like that we went from talking to wedding planners to oncologists.

Our decision to marry was born from a place of urgency and love. After my diagnosis we were faced with an uncertain future, with treatment looming and no end in sight. In the midst of the uncertainty, we realized we wanted to fully commit to each other, no matter what lay ahead. We started our journey living our vows on the ‘sickness’ note, and boy did Conner show up for his vow EVERY SINGLE DAY.

We are now finally having a full-circle experience as we prepare for our Indian wedding in Bangalore, where I can honor my Indian heritage and share this with loved ones who have stood by us.

#weddingthrowback #insicknessandinhealth #cancerdiagnosis

latestPosts.caption:
After 2 years I’m finally comfortable wearing my badge of honor, the chemo port scar, with no cover up or touch ups⚡️It took a while to look at it without reminders of the nasty chemo cocktails that were infused through the port. Now I look at it as a scar that served as a lifeline. 

Couldn’t have pulled off this confidence without the man in my arms, who encourages me to be authentic everyday and celebrates all my wins - micro, mini, mega, all of it! Love you @conner_orourke ❤️

Happy birthday to my light, my love, my strength, my all 🩷 I wouldn’t have gotten through a single day in these past two years without you by my side. If god sends challenges to those ready to handle it, I was more ready than I ever knew possible, just because I had you by my side. Your unwavering kindness, patience, love, and determination to get us to the finish line kept me going. You are my biggest gift and I can’t believe how lucky I am to have found you. This is our year and I can’t wait for all the new adventures with you🩷 🧿

Thank you for capturing us in the first photo @photosbytiaco ✨

latestPosts.caption:
In May of last year my wife received a nightmare of a phone call. 

What she did after the call will be remembered forever by those of us who are lucky enough to be close to her.

She smiled.

How? While I still honestly don’t know the answer, I think I know why. 

She smiled for us. She smiled to tell us she was ok when she wasn’t. She smiled to give her family and friends strength. She smiled for all the other cancer patients AND all the amazing nurses and doctors because my wife is truly selfless and altruistic. 

She smiled for everyone out there going through  tremendous difficulty to let them know they are tougher than they ever knew possible.

While my wife is looking up at me in this first picture, I’ll be the one looking up to her forever. 

Jagriti just completed over a year of treatment and is now cancer free! 😃
